<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06121007 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06121007 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; MANUFACTURING; PRODUCT; STATISTIC; ECONOMY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods fell 2.8 percent in March, thefifth drop in a row for that key economic barometer of industry plans forproduction, the government said today.;    The Commerce Department said neworders for both durable and non-durable goods totaled a seasonally adjusted$226.6 billion, down from $233.1 billion in February.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  5TH STRAIGHT DROP FOR FACTORY ORDERS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The decline had been expected following last week's reported plunge inMarch orders for durable goods -- items from trucks to turbines expected tolast more than three years.;    Although it was the fourth decline in durableorders in five months, the 4.9 percent decrease, to $111.8 billion, was not assharp as the 6.2 percent drop first reported. Still, most major categoriesfell.;    Orders for non-durable goods also fell, down 0.6 percent to $114.9billion. Much of the decline was attributed to chemicals and petroleumproducts.;    The decrease in overall orders suggests even more job losses inthe manufacturing sector, which has seen a 1.2 million erosion in payrollssince January 1989. Factory unemployment grew by 92,000 in March. And the keycategory of non-defense capital goods fell 5 percent, to $32.1 billion, itsthird consecutive monthly loss. This category often is a barometer of industryplans to expand and modernize.;    Orders for durable goods dropped to theirlowest level since September 1987, when they totaled $111.8 billion. Only theindustrial machinery and equipment category posted a gain, up a slight 0.2percent to $19.9 billion.;    Electronic and other electrical equipment ordersplunged 13.5 percent to $15.6 billion.;    Transportation orders were off 5percent, to $28.3 billion. Excluding transportation, orders fell 2.5 percent.;   Orders for primary metals fell 1 percent, to $9.7 billion.;    Theoften-volatile defense orders plummeted 18.5 percent, to $6.5 billion, aftergaining 3.1 percent in February and 12.3 percent a month earlier. Excludingthis category, orders fell 2.2 percent.; Shipments of manufactured goods alsofell, down 1.9 percent to $228.8 billion for the fifth straight decline.Shipments were at their lowest level since October 1988 when they totaled$228.3 billion.;    Unfilled orders, an indication of how busy factories willbe in coming months, slipped 0.4 percent to $524.9 billion.;    Inventorieswere down 0.6 percent, to $386.3 billion, their third decline in four months.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910430  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  376  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday April 30, 199100121007,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>